## 3. Natural Mapping of Split-Ergativity

One of the hardest things for human students learning Sumerian is its **split-ergative** grammar system. In English, the subject of a sentence is treated the same whether the verb is active or passive (*"I ran"* vs. *"I hit the ball"*). In Sumerian, the grammatical case changes completely depending on whether the verb has a direct object or what tense it is in.

Because EME-GIR can support a split-ergative logic model natively:

* It can handle variables that change their access properties based on whether they are the *agent* (doing the action) or the *patient* (receiving the action).
* A compiler built this way automatically flags grammatically impossible translations as **runtime errors**, instantly filtering out thousands of incorrect machine-translation guesses.

